<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>wake sleeping dogs • wake snakes</xh5><p> <i>wake sleeping dogs</i>—(also: wake a sleeping dog) create trouble interfering with a precarious situation which is quiet: Some say that it is too early to fix any rules, or that it is really dangerous to do so: it might <u>wake sleeping dogs</u>. <i>Cf.: let sleeping dogs lie</i>—refrain from stirring up potential trouble: How many times had he told her it was over, that she needed to move on and <u>let sleeping dogs lie</u>?</p><p><i>wake snakes</i>—(dated sl.) cause trouble or disturbance: But what about some phrases that we don’t hear very often anymore? I found some of these quite interesting. To <u>wake snakes</u>, meant to raise a ruckus.</p> </entry>
